{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584080"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:37:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:37:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14392"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14392"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7087"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62286"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7087"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14392"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47733"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4900"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7200"},{"type":"tags","id":"7215"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17307"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62286","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62286"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe recurrent laryngeal nerves are branches of the vagus nerve that supply motor function to the intrinsic muscles of the larynx. These nerves have a unique anatomical course, with the right and left sides differing in their path.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures does the right recurrent laryngeal nerve loop around?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subclavian artery","Arch of aorta","Common carotid artery","Internal thoracic artery","Vertebral artery"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe right recurrent laryngeal nerve progressing by having a loop around the \u003Cstrong\u003Esubclavian artery\u003C/strong\u003E before ascending to the larynx. This is in contrast to the left recurrent laryngeal nerve, which loops around the \u003Cstrong\u003Earch of aorta\u003C/strong\u003E. Both nerves then ascend in the tracheoesophageal groove to supply motor innervation to most intrinsic muscles of the larynx (except the cricothyroid, which is innervated by the external branch of the superior laryngeal nerve). The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommon carotid artery\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal thoracic artery\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Evertebral artery\u003C/strong\u003E are not involved in the path of either recurrent laryngeal nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis anatomical difference is important to understand for several reasons:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt explains why the left recurrent laryngeal nerve has a longer course than the right.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is clinically relevant in thyroid and cardiac surgeries, where these nerves may be at risk of injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt helps explain why certain pathologies (e.g., an enlarged aortic arch) might affect the left recurrent laryngeal nerve but not the right.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The right recurrent laryngeal nerve progresses by looping around right subclavian artery before ascending to the larynx.","The left recurrent laryngeal nerve loops, in its path, around the arch of the aorta and this creates an anatomical asymmetry."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Tubbs, R. S., Rizk, E. B., Shoja, M. M., Loukas, M., Barbaro, N., \u0026 Spinner, R. J.  Nerves and Nerve Injuries: Vol 2: Pain, Treatment, Injury, Disease and Future Directions. Academic Press. 2015. https://doi.org/10.1016/C2014-0-03700-8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47733"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14392"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47733"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T16:28:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T16:29:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7087"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62286"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"des